# PMTool WinUI + SQLite Bug Prevention

## 1) WinUI XAML Type Safety
- Never use shorthand like `ColumnDefinitions="Auto,*"` or `RowDefinitions="Auto,*"` in this repo.
- Always write explicit blocks:
  - `<Grid.ColumnDefinitions><ColumnDefinition Width="Auto"/><ColumnDefinition Width="*"/></Grid.ColumnDefinitions>`
  - `<Grid.RowDefinitions><RowDefinition Height="Auto"/><RowDefinition Height="*"/></Grid.RowDefinitions>`
- Keep `Width`/`Height` as `GridLength` (`Auto`, `*`, `2*`) and avoid numeric-only values in definitions.

## 2) Build Input Hygiene
- Do not introduce extra generated-source folders that are not excluded by SDK defaults (e.g. `obj-probe`).
- If such folders are required, ensure they are excluded via project file:
  - `<DefaultItemExcludes>$(DefaultItemExcludes);obj-probe\**;obj-probe/**</DefaultItemExcludes>`
- If build shows duplicate `App.g.i.cs`/`InitializeComponent`/`Program.Main`, first suspect generated file double-inclusion.

## 3) SQLite Backward-Compatible Schema Ensure
- In `EnsureAsync` startup schema code, never create indexes that assume a column always exists in legacy DBs.
- Before index creation, query `PRAGMA table_info(<table>)` and branch by existing columns.
- For old schemas, create degraded fallback indexes (project-based or active-only) instead of failing startup.

## 4) Migration Ordering Guard
- Startup order must remain: `ProjectsSchema.EnsureAsync` -> `SchemaMigration.ApplyAsync`.
- Therefore, `ProjectsSchema` must be legacy-safe; all non-backward-compatible SQL belongs in migration steps.

## 5) Final Validation Gate
- Before finishing any change touching XAML/DB schema:
  1) run `dotnet build src/PMTool.sln -c Debug`
  2) verify app startup path (OnLaunched + initialization) does not throw schema or XAML parse errors.
